div.p:
Perhaps the simplest and most cost-effective manner to prepare inorganic materials is through precipitation from solution. This process involves a nucleation and a growth stage. As the nuclei formed approach a critical concentration, additional reactants can either attach to the existing nuclei, leading to particle growth, or form new nuclei. Naturally, the morphology of the precipitates produced depends on which of these two competitive steps prevails, but they both proceed so quickly that it is difficult to control them to promote the growth of particles and materials with desired morphologies. What Wei-Hong Lai and co-workers have now done is to judiciously tune the reaction system by adjusting the electrolytic dissociation (

 α

) of the precursors and the supersaturation (

 S

) of the solution to favour the growth of specific morphologies, without the need for any additives.

From the nucleation stage (blue and red spheres represent different species), adjusting the electrolytic dissociation (α) of the reactants and the supersaturation (

 S

) of the solution affect the rate of nucleation and the growth processes. Varying the conditions in turn promotes the synthesis of materials with either 1D-, 2D- or 3D-morphologies.
